ng of the Atlantic slave trade.The contributors cast new light upon questions that have framed the study of slavery in the Americas for decades. The book investigates such topics as the illegal slave trade in Cuba, the Creole slave revolt in the U.S., and the debate between pro- and antislavery factions over the interstate slave trade in the South. Together, the authors offer fresh and provocative insights into the interrelations of capitalism, sovereignty, and slavery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSlave tradezBrazilxHistoryy19th centuryvCongresses. 0aSlave tradezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th centuryvCongresses. 0aSlave tradezWest Indies, BritishxHistoryy19th centuryvCongresses. 0aSlaveryzBrazilxHistoryy19th centuryvCongresses. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th centuryvCongresses. 0aSlaveryzWest Indies, BritishxHistoryy19th centuryvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBaptist, Edward E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckles, Hilary McD., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Daina Ramey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, David Brion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeyle, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrescher, Seymour, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, Lacy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGudmestad, Robert H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Walter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabul